13:46.480 --> 13:49.880
the notes were spelling out
messages for the Resistance.

13:49.880 --> 13:53.040
How would you use this
to send a secret message?

13:53.040 --> 13:55.200
That's going to need a big egg!

13:55.200 --> 13:57.400
LAUGHTER

13:57.400 --> 13:59.640
Someone would know the cypher.

13:59.640 --> 14:01.560
So, E = B...

14:01.560 --> 14:03.120
You don't need to know anything.

14:03.120 --> 14:05.480
Oh, is it the way you fold it?
Does it then make a message?

14:05.480 --> 14:08.160
It is the way you wrap
it around something. Wow!

14:08.160 --> 14:09.240
It's called a scytale.

14:09.240 --> 14:11.520
It's an ancient Greek way
to hide messages.

14:11.520 --> 14:14.880
All it required was that the person
sending and the person receiving

14:14.880 --> 14:17.600
had the same size stick.
That's cool.

14:17.600 --> 14:19.080
And then you would just send this,

14:19.080 --> 14:20.760
which could be wrapped up
quite small

14:20.760 --> 14:25.320
and you wrap it around like this
and it says,

14:25.320 --> 14:27.520
"This is a scytale."

14:27.520 --> 14:28.720
Isn't it clever?

14:28.720 --> 14:30.240
That's very clever. I know.

14:30.240 --> 14:32.360
I'd love it if you got it
and that was the message.

14:32.360 --> 14:36.640
And then you just had to reply,
"I know what a scytale is!

14:36.640 --> 14:38.520
"It was my idea to use 'em!

14:38.520 --> 14:40.440
"Can you please stick to the plan?

14:40.440 --> 14:42.800
"We're trying to
bring down a government here!

14:42.800 --> 14:45.720
"I don't need you to tell me what
the equipment is that we used!"

14:45.720 --> 14:47.800
Wow, this is so cool, right?

14:47.800 --> 14:49.600
The rest of it just is gibberish.

14:49.600 --> 14:51.760
It would take you a while to work
out. It also says...

14:51.760 --> 14:53.720
SHE MUMBLES GIBBERISH

14:53.720 --> 14:56.320
That's the Danish version.
It IS the Danish version!

14:56.320 --> 14:57.600
PHONE RINGS

14:57.600 --> 15:00.840
Oh, sorry, I'll just get out
my handkerchief.

15:02.800 --> 15:05.080
Er, hello? Yes?

15:05.080 --> 15:07.840
No. No, Moneypenny, I've told you
not to ring me at work.

15:07.840 --> 15:09.920
Yeah.

15:09.920 --> 15:11.480
OK. The Banker?

15:11.480 --> 15:13.480
LAUGHTER

15:15.160 --> 15:17.800
Who would use a secure phone
like this?

15:17.800 --> 15:20.920
Commissioner Gordon.
Commissioner Gordon!

15:20.920 --> 15:24.000
That's such a good reference.
Anybody else? Who would use...?

15:24.000 --> 15:28.280
Again, this is a totally
unnecessary Chaponda back story!

15:28.280 --> 15:31.960
But we needed one of those
because we were always bugged.

15:31.960 --> 15:36.800
Right. And the reason I know this
is, in Kenya, the Malawi ambassador

15:36.800 --> 15:40.160
happened to be a high-school
friend of my mum,

15:40.160 --> 15:43.480
and gave my mum
a bunch of my dad's secrets.

15:43.480 --> 15:45.240
Really?! Yeah.

15:45.240 --> 15:48.040
When you say secrets, like...

15:48.040 --> 15:50.920
He's been "calling this woman",
what's going on? Oh, secrets!

15:50.920 --> 15:52.560
Yes. Wow!

15:52.560 --> 15:54.920
Have you ever had therapy,
because...?

15:54.920 --> 15:58.600
Is it too late to bring up?
My dad is the Mayor of Kettering.

16:00.080 --> 16:02.040
On numerous occasions,

16:02.040 --> 16:04.280
people have tried to push him over,

16:04.280 --> 16:07.680
and I had to meet a spy
in a Harvester once.

16:09.640 --> 16:11.680
And, let me tell you, he looked

16:11.680 --> 16:15.680
more like a bass player
in a prog band, this man.

16:17.000 --> 16:20.480
You were OK, though? And I DO
go to therapy, just so you know.

16:20.480 --> 16:24.280
So, who might have had
a red telephone? A head of state?

16:24.280 --> 16:25.920
Yeah. President?

16:25.920 --> 16:29.320
So, the one that we normally think
of is the US and Russia hotline.

16:29.320 --> 16:31.080
It was often called
the red telephone.

16:31.080 --> 16:33.600
It was neither red nor a telephone.
What?! Yeah, I know.

16:33.600 --> 16:35.680
I'm destroying things for you!
What?!

16:35.680 --> 16:38.960
So June 1963, we'd just
had the Cuban Missile Crisis,

16:38.960 --> 16:41.440
and it took 12 hours at
that time to get messages

16:41.440 --> 16:42.600
backwards and forwards.

16:42.600 --> 16:45.720
They agreed to establish a sort of
direct form of communication.

16:45.720 --> 16:49.440
The very first message sent
by the Americans in August 1963

16:49.440 --> 16:52.880
read, "The quick brown fox jumped
over the lazy dog's back.

16:52.880 --> 16:55.920
"1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 0."

16:55.920 --> 16:57.760
You had to wrap it round a stick!

16:57.760 --> 16:59.360
Why would they send that?

16:59.360 --> 17:01.800
Because it has every letter
in the world. Uses every letter!

17:01.800 --> 17:03.160
Yeah. Which is called? Oh!

17:03.160 --> 17:04.680
The alphabet.

17:04.680 --> 17:06.040
LAUGHTER

17:07.280 --> 17:10.080
They were trying to show that
they could send all the letters

17:10.080 --> 17:12.280
and that they could actually
communicate directly, because,

17:12.280 --> 17:13.680
in fact, the system consisted not

17:13.680 --> 17:15.600
of telephones,
but of teletype machines.

17:15.600 --> 17:18.360
So there were four teletype
machines in Moscow, four more in

17:18.360 --> 17:21.280
the Soviet embassy in Washington,
and the message was sent over

17:21.280 --> 17:23.600
a 10,000-mile-long
transatlantic cable.

17:23.600 --> 17:26.240
Why is it called the red telephone,
if there's no red telephone?!

17:26.240 --> 17:27.920
It maybe just sounds better.

17:27.920 --> 17:32.160
The 1971 system updated
the use of a satellite connection,

17:32.160 --> 17:35.280
and, most recently, they've
upgraded to a fibre optic link

17:35.280 --> 17:38.920
allowing both email and finally
talking, but only recently. Wow.

17:38.920 --> 17:42.080
There were red secure telephones
in the UK. They were introduced

17:42.080 --> 17:45.040
in the 1950s. Oh! This, and that's
why I was so careful touching it,

17:45.040 --> 17:48.440
is a real Pickwick phone.
It's been lent to us by GCHQ. Wow!

17:48.440 --> 17:50.320
So the Pickwick system was in place

17:50.320 --> 17:53.600
and used during the Cuban Missile
Crisis for secure communication,

17:53.600 --> 17:56.120
but it was between the then
Prime Minister, Harold Macmillan,

17:56.120 --> 17:57.320
and President Kennedy.

17:57.320 --> 17:59.800
And basically this would attach
to the cypher unit and that sort of

17:59.800 --> 18:02.320
mashed up the speech
and prevented eavesdroppers from

18:02.320 --> 18:04.840
understanding what was going on.
What I like is the British Army,

18:04.840 --> 18:06.280
they thought this
is the way to do it.

18:06.280 --> 18:08.640
They used to hire operators
with strong regional accents

18:08.640 --> 18:10.880
so that if anybody was
eavesdropping, they thought,

18:10.880 --> 18:13.360
"Well, they'll never understand
what they bloody said!"

18:13.360 --> 18:17.480
IN WELSH ACCENT: Listen, we're
going to invade at 20 past 5, OK?

18:17.480 --> 18:20.040
And it's going to be, oh,
it's going to go mad, I tell you!

18:20.040 --> 18:22.840
Everyone's going to be kicking off,
you're not going to believe it!

18:22.840 --> 18:26.400
Understand? All right? Ta, bye.
All right, bye, bye, bye.

18:26.400 --> 18:29.440
You wouldn't know. You'd
have no idea what was going on.

18:29.440 --> 18:32.680
Even Welsh people! We do have,
and I think this is seriously cool,

18:32.680 --> 18:34.240
we have another secure phone.

18:34.240 --> 18:36.640
It's just over on the table
cos I don't want to touch it.

18:36.640 --> 18:37.960
It's also incredibly heavy.

18:37.960 --> 18:41.120
It's called Brahms, and it is
a portable, secure line

18:41.120 --> 18:42.640
that comes in a suitcase.

18:42.640 --> 18:45.080
And this is the one that
was used by Margaret Thatcher

18:45.080 --> 18:47.360
during the Falklands War.

18:47.360 --> 18:49.320
Wow. Wow. This is very cool,
isn't it?

18:49.320 --> 18:51.920
She was able to open it,
James, which was nice.

18:51.920 --> 18:55.880
We are joined virtually now
by Dr David Abrutat,

18:55.880 --> 18:58.880
GCHQ's Departmental Historian.

18:58.880 --> 19:03.320
Dr David is one of a very few number
of GCHQ employees to be avowed.

19:03.320 --> 19:06.080
What does that mean, David,
you are avowed?

19:06.080 --> 19:09.480
Essentially it means
I'm publicly known,

19:09.480 --> 19:13.240
and, as the department's historian,
my role's to tell the story

19:13.240 --> 19:16.560
of our organisation's history
over the last 100 years.

19:16.560 --> 19:19.600
So, tell me, the one I want
to hear about is, there was

19:19.600 --> 19:23.160
a secret line called Sigsaly.
Can you tell me about Sigsaly?

19:23.160 --> 19:27.120
During the Second World War,
the British and American governments

19:27.120 --> 19:30.480
needed to talk frequently
on a secure line.

19:30.480 --> 19:35.600
And in November 1942, GCHQ's
Alan Turing went over on a liaison

19:35.600 --> 19:39.560
visit to the States, to the Bell
Laboratories, who were researching

19:39.560 --> 19:42.480
and developing a new secure
communications system,

19:42.480 --> 19:43.960
which was called Sigsaly.

19:43.960 --> 19:47.240
And it was an absolute monster,
it weighed 50 tonnes.

19:47.240 --> 19:49.520
It included 40 racks of equipment

19:49.520 --> 19:52.720
and drew something like
30 kilowatts of power.

19:52.720 --> 19:56.640
And it was certainly known
by the users as the Green Hornet

19:56.640 --> 19:59.920
because of its irritating
buzzing noise on the line.

19:59.920 --> 20:05.200
And the first Sigsaly was installed
in the Pentagon in the States,

20:05.200 --> 20:09.240
and the second was installed
in the basement of Selfridges

20:09.240 --> 20:10.640
in Oxford Street,

20:10.640 --> 20:15.640
so certainly on the first trial run
on July 15th 1943, Winston Churchill

20:15.640 --> 20:19.120
was using this piece of equipment
in the basement

20:19.120 --> 20:21.840
of Selfridges
before they put in extension lines

20:21.840 --> 20:25.080
to 10 Downing Street,
if the rumours are true.

20:25.080 --> 20:27.640
Fantastic. Alan, did you want
to ask anything?

20:27.640 --> 20:31.000
Well, I've seen Thatcher's
briefcase, and I just wondered,

20:31.000 --> 20:33.960
did she take it on holiday?
Did she carry it herself?

20:33.960 --> 20:36.360
DR ABRUTAT: Did Margaret Thatcher
ever go on holiday?

20:36.360 --> 20:38.200
ALAN: Perhaps not!

20:38.200 --> 20:42.360
DR ABRUTAT: The briefcase phone
you've got is called Brahms,

20:42.360 --> 20:45.320
which was developed in
the early 1980s, and it was used

20:45.320 --> 20:48.880
by the British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, at the time,

20:48.880 --> 20:51.760
during the Falklands conflict,
to communicate securely

20:51.760 --> 20:55.880
with her Cabinet and to the senior
military officers of the time.

20:55.880 --> 20:57.400
Well, it's been fascinating.

20:57.400 --> 20:59.880
I don't know if you send love
to everybody at GCHQ!

20:59.880 --> 21:01.960
I send love to everyone at GCHQ.

21:01.960 --> 21:04.760
And thank you very much,
Dr David Abrutat.

21:04.760 --> 21:07.680
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE
Thank you.

21:07.680 --> 21:10.040
Now, complete this sentence.

21:10.040 --> 21:15.240
If you're invited to a penetration
party, it's best to practise safe...

21:19.520 --> 21:21.720
Safe words.

21:21.720 --> 21:24.200
In case things get hairy.
That's very...

21:24.200 --> 21:25.960
And I'm worried that you know that!

21:28.880 --> 21:30.600
What are they penetrating?

21:30.600 --> 21:32.120
That's the question.

21:32.120 --> 21:35.080
Is it a person? No, it isn't.
Thank goodness for that.

21:35.080 --> 21:37.720
You are best to practise
safe cracking.

21:37.720 --> 21:40.960
Penetration party
is a perfectly innocent phrase

21:40.960 --> 21:42.680
used by safe crackers to describe

21:42.680 --> 21:46.600
an all-night event
where they practise opening safes.

21:46.600 --> 21:48.800
Wow! And it was invented
by accident,

21:48.800 --> 21:51.400
so there was a safe cracker
who was called Dave McOmie.

21:51.400 --> 21:53.600
He's a bit of a legend,
this guy, OK. He edits

21:53.600 --> 21:56.120
the International
Safecracker magazine.

21:56.120 --> 21:59.320
Wow. He looks exactly like
I thought he would.

22:00.600 --> 22:03.000
That's not even him.
That's a general look, frankly.

22:03.000 --> 22:05.280
Can we talk about the guy
in the background

22:05.280 --> 22:06.800
with the orange back support?

22:06.800 --> 22:08.760
Yeah, that is worrying, isn't it?

22:08.760 --> 22:10.240
I really want to be in the shot

22:10.240 --> 22:12.600
where he was buying that
back support, going,

22:12.600 --> 22:15.000
"I'm going to
a penetration party later.

22:15.000 --> 22:17.560
"I'm going to need
a back support for it.

22:17.560 --> 22:21.360
"Just the best one you've got.
It's a big penetration party.

22:21.360 --> 22:25.160
"A lot of guys." "This one
comes with a free matching cap."

22:25.160 --> 22:26.680
"Oh, perfect!"

22:26.680 --> 22:29.600
He's the only one with the
headphones on! Who's he talking to?

22:29.600 --> 22:31.480
There's someone in the safe.

22:31.480 --> 22:35.000
IN MUFFLED VOICE: "I'm inside now.
Are wearing the back support? Over."

22:35.000 --> 22:38.240
"Yeah, but I'm the only one.
I'm standing out."

22:38.240 --> 22:41.760
So they were at a convention
in Philadelphia and one

22:41.760 --> 22:44.000
of the attendees mentioned
that he had a warehouse

22:44.000 --> 22:46.440
filled with about 80 safes,
which all needed opening.

22:46.440 --> 22:49.240
So they decided to do
a masterclass with these 80 things.

22:49.240 --> 22:50.880
Everybody got their equipment.

22:50.880 --> 22:53.320
They spent all night,
all night working on the safes.

22:53.320 --> 22:55.480
They managed to open
every single one of them.

22:55.480 --> 22:58.120
And now it's become a thing.
People have penetration parties.

22:58.120 --> 23:00.720
But how WOULD you open the safe?
Do you know the different ways?

23:00.720 --> 23:03.560
No idea. Twice I've moved house,

23:03.560 --> 23:07.160
and there's been a safe, big safe,
in the house I couldn't get in.

23:07.160 --> 23:09.360
And the second time
it happened to me, I thought,

23:09.360 --> 23:12.760
"I want to get rid of that." It took
six men. I wasn't one of them -

23:12.760 --> 23:16.760
I didn't have a back support.
No. Incredibly heavy thing.

23:16.760 --> 23:18.800
And to this day,
I don't know what was in it.

23:18.800 --> 23:21.760
Oh, wow. I mean, the weight of it,
presumably loads of gold.

23:23.840 --> 23:25.160
Oops!

23:26.920 --> 23:30.120
The best thing, if the mechanism
has slipped a bit, you can work

23:30.120 --> 23:33.200
on the dial. The easiest thing is
what these guys are doing here,

23:33.200 --> 23:35.280
which is to drill a hole.
I love this.

23:35.280 --> 23:37.520
"Just use a sledgehammer,"
it says. That's it.

23:37.520 --> 23:39.760
Just get in and biff it.

23:39.760 --> 23:43.000
I might go to a penetration party
and ask if they run

23:43.000 --> 23:45.440
a course for briefcases.

23:49.320 --> 23:53.400
"I've been struggling lately
and I'm working my way up

23:53.400 --> 23:56.720
"to a safe, but first of all,
I'm only

23:56.720 --> 23:58.960
"halfway there with a briefcase.

23:58.960 --> 24:02.240
"I'll just sit in the corner
while you do the safe stuff."

24:02.240 --> 24:04.560
IN AMERICAN ACCENT:
James, put on the back support,

24:04.560 --> 24:06.040
strap in and watch.

24:07.680 --> 24:10.040
There are other ways
to break into secure buildings

24:10.040 --> 24:12.600
if you think outside the box.
This is a wonderful story.

24:12.600 --> 24:15.120
In 1971, there was
an activist group called

24:15.120 --> 24:17.960
the Citizens' Commission
To Investigate The FBI,

24:17.960 --> 24:21.760
and they targeted a draft board
in Delaware, and to gain access,

24:21.760 --> 24:24.600
all they did was they left
a note on the door that read,

24:24.600 --> 24:26.600
"Please don't lock
this door tonight."

24:26.600 --> 24:29.080
No! Yeah. And nobody did.

24:29.080 --> 24:31.200
So it completely worked.

24:32.160 --> 24:35.360
They went in and stole
everything that they needed.

24:35.360 --> 24:37.400
That's genius! Isn't that brilliant?

24:37.400 --> 24:40.200
And it revealed evidence of
massive wrongdoing and spying

24:40.200 --> 24:42.640
and criminal activity
by Edgar Hoover's FBI,

24:42.640 --> 24:44.360
which was then sent to journalists.

24:44.360 --> 24:47.320
And 200 agents went on a manhunt
to try and find out who did it.

24:47.320 --> 24:49.400
And they never did find the people.
CARIAD GASPS

24:49.400 --> 24:53.080
Another way to break into a safe is
to bypass the doors entirely, OK?

24:53.080 --> 24:57.440
I love this story. 1836, the Bank of
England got an anonymous letter when

24:57.440 --> 25:00.640
the sender claimed to have access
to their stash of gold, OK?

25:00.640 --> 25:03.200
So, offered to prove it by
meeting staff from the bank

25:03.200 --> 25:05.600
in the vault at a time
of their choosing.

25:05.600 --> 25:08.040
So, time was set, the bank managers
go into the vault

25:08.040 --> 25:11.920
and they saw a man appearing up
through the floorboards,

25:11.920 --> 25:14.720
and he had been working on
the sewers and he had discovered,

25:14.720 --> 25:17.640
by fluke, that you could
get up into the safe.

25:17.640 --> 25:19.760
He didn't take anything
and the bank was so grateful,

25:19.760 --> 25:24.040
they gave him £800, which is
about 80 grand in today's money,

25:24.040 --> 25:26.480
and arranged for the vault
to be made more secure.

25:26.480 --> 25:29.160
Wow! Somebody going,
"The floorboards!"

25:29.160 --> 25:32.000
I love that he must have been
standing there covered in shit,

25:32.000 --> 25:36.200
from the sewers, being like,
"See? I got right in."

25:36.200 --> 25:37.760
And they're like, "That's amazing.

25:37.760 --> 25:39.720
"Stand back, just don't
come too near, Dave."

25:39.720 --> 25:42.120
He could have nicked it all
because they didn't know about it.

25:42.120 --> 25:44.760
He could have taken a bar each day
and they wouldn't even notice.

25:44.760 --> 25:49.160
No idea. Anyway, moving on.
